Building blocks of logical thought and how they may come about in infancy/childhood.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Strengths: Good class discussions. Weaknesses: Class is heavily paper based, which is what a seminar is but maybe more interactive parts or in-class demonstrations would have been fun.

A major weakness of this class is the fact that students have no idea how well they are performing in the class at any point. Grades for assignments turned in in September were posted after classes were over. Also, the majority of the class did not touch on cognitive development until the last few weeks of class.
The weekly reading response is a bit much but overall the content is consistently interesting g and relevant

strengths: prof was willing to change paper deadlines

weaknesses: midterm paper outline due during family weekend, readings were dense, reading responses took a long time

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, if youre interested in infant cognition.

I would not recommend this course to another student, because even though the topics of the class might be interesting, the format, feedback structure, and communication were all exceptionally subpar.
If you are interested in any aspect of logical thought in humans and other animals this is the right course to take.

I would recommend this course to another student interested in logic. I made the mistake of not looking into the readings and assuming that the course would be more focused on development, but it is mostly focused on logic. if you're interested in that, I think you'd enjoy this course!
